  "prompt": "Neuroscience: How is the elephant parietal lobes different from the human parietal lobes?",
  "response": "To compare elephant and human parietal lobes, I'll provide key differences based on current neuroscience research:\n\n1. Size and Complexity:\n- Elephants: Larger overall brain size relative to body weight\n- Humans: Proportionally smaller but more complex neural networks\n\n2. Functional Specialization:\n- Elephants: More focused on spatial awareness and sensory integration\n- Humans: More advanced in abstract reasoning and complex spatial processing\n\n3. Neuronal Density:\n- Elephants: Lower neuronal density in parietal regions\n- Humans: Higher neuronal density with more intricate connections\n\n4. Sensory Processing:\n- Elephants: Enhanced tactile processing through trunk and highly sensitive skin\n- Humans: More advanced multi-modal sensory integration\n\n5. Structural Differences:\n- Elephants: More uniform cortical organization\n- Humans: More specialized cortical subdivisions\n\n6. Cognitive Functions:\n- Elephants: Stronger spatial memory and navigation\n- Humans: More abstract spatial reasoning and mathematical capabilities\n\nWhile similarities exist, significant structural and functional differences distinguish elephant and human parietal lobes, reflecting evolutionary adaptations to different environmental and cognitive demands.\n\nNote: Comparative neuroanatomy research in this specific area is still developing.",
